GREAT brunch spot! Food: Crawfish Beignet all the way! So savory and succulent; light and fluffy flour surrounding the crawfish. Yum. The Hangtown Fry with crispy oyster, bacon & scallion eggs is divine paired with the cheesy grits. I'm originally from the South, so I know grits and biscuits. Believe me -- Brenda's is the best I've had so far. Service: pretty good. Kept my watermelon ice tea full the entire time. Took a little while to give me my check, but otherwise, on point. Tip: Don't go during peak brunch hours!

We came in a group of 5 around 6:30pm on a Saturday and waited about half an hour. Service wasn't the fastest but they were busy. I had shrimp and grits. Shrimp is slightly overcooked while grits are swimming in grease. I left a good chuck of the grits because of that. I've had shrimp and grits in a few restaurants in Louisiana and they weren't like that. Chicken etouffee wasn't well flavored imo. Fried chicken got good feedback. Although I didn't try my friend's crawfish beignet; I looked at her peeling off most of the dough only to find a small chuck of fish. While mostly dough could work on sweet beignet, I'm not sure it's a good idea for savory. Price was decent but overall I just wasn't impressed with the quality.

If you love rich, cheesy food, this is definitely the way to go. Unfortunately, I'm not into that, but I'm not dinging this place on that. I had high expectations. And this place just didn't meet them. Everything is moderately priced, (between $8-$13) for most things and comes out quickly. Watermelon sweet tea was pretty legit. Free refills too. Not super sweet like mcdonalds sweet tea, but if you're a fan of watermelon and a fan of sweet tea, this is the way to go. Friends loved the crawfish beignets, 3 large beignets for $8. Plain beignets were about $5. Delicious beignets that satisfy my craving for beignets (not quite as great as cafe du monde's in New Orleans). Catfish po boy had great seasoning on the catfish, although the beef medallion dish was a bit on the lacking side. Quick tips: 1) Get there before 10:00am and you won't have to wait too terribly long 2) $3.00 meter parking per hour, so make sure you have your quarters ready!

Six stars. Greatest breakfast in the history of mankind. The food was some of the best I've had, the atmosphere and the staff were amazing, and the price points were more than reasonable. I've been dissatisfied with a number of restaurants in the Union Square area but this was not one of them.

Sitting at the front of Brenda's amid the casual whimsy of its New Orleans-inspired overtone with whispers of sophistication, I had an epiphany that the 5 pounds i had hoped to lose by summer would make no great difference in the grand scheme of my life, whereas missing out on the banana foster french toast would be a regret I'm positive would burden me on my deathbed. And alas, my 2 months of hard work counting calories and determination escaped me on a passing plate of brioche covered in richly decadent flambéed bananas and rum sauce with a side of freshly whipped cream. After I pushed my last few bites of toast around every nook and crevice of my plate to summon any forgotten syrup, I regretted nothing. And oh the beignets! I'm still not sure if these are a godsend of heavenly creation, or the devil's efforts to tempt me into commitment of 4 deadly sins in one meal - lust, gluttony, greed and sloth, cleverly disguised as chocolate, apple, crawfish and plain. Known on the menu as "beignet flight", if this course is a sin let the arrival gate be hell and I'd still board first. I'd tell you about my friend's creole veggie omelette too, but by the time I looked up from my watermelon sweet tea he had already inhaled it.. but not before I ravenously snatched his airy, buttery biscuit of layered flaky perfection! And whether the jam with which i drowned it in was made by tenderly smashing freshly-picked organic strawberries with loving hands each morning or a carefully selected store-bought jar, i know not and care not for it tasted hopelessly delectable and was the most luscious pairing I could ever hope to again grace my plate for breakfasts to come. MUST GO.

I've been here about 6 times now, so this review is based on substantial experience. The food is good. Real good. This is because it is loaded with all of the things that are bad for you (butter, sugar, salt, butter --- all in generous portions), and you will consequently feel like a bad person for eating here. An extremely comforted bad person. Make plans to go the gym afterward. The food philosophy seems to be: anything on this menu can be improved by making the portions larger and adding cheese or butter pecan sauce. And I agree. It's a very busy restaurant, so go on off hours --- as in, hit your lunch at 11:00am, or after 1:30pm. Don't even bother trying for brunch on the weekends.

Went back for a 2nd visit during our 4 day sf stay. Had to wait 30+ minutes for a table but so worth it. The coffee and biscuits alone make the experience!

So so amazing. Great for trendy lunch or dinner: Order: "50/50" po-boy shrimp & oysters - amazing (and enormous) Order: Beignet flight - where else can you even get this?!? The crawfish beignet was just okay, so if you're on the fence, I'd go sweet over savory

As I crossed the street toward Brenda's I saw a line that went around the corner and then some, and thought, "AW SHEEEEEEET" (and not the good kind). This would be my 3rd attempt at eating here without a 2 hour long wait. So, backup plan (always have a backup, even if it is saltine crackers that have been crushed by sitting on them) in my pocket: order to go. Crawfish beignets, cheese grits, cream biscuits, hash, the Hangtown Fry (crispy oyster, bacon, scallion scramble), Egg & Bacon Tartine...this was my TO GO order on our way to Napa. I think this was quite possibly the most delicious drive I've ever had. To coast on a drive with Brenda's cheese grits melting in your mouth...that's somethin' else. With 3 chalkboards worth of names willing to wait 2+ hours for a table, I think Brenda's has definitely earned its culinary street cred. Even my order took about 30-45 minutes, but it was well worth it. This is your true blue southern brunch at its best. It's the right amount of crunchy, buttery, savory... I still don't know that I could wait 2 hours to get a table here, but eating at Brenda's is like a giant Southern cream biscuit hugging your stomach and stroking / soothing you with an oversized strip of crispy bacon. Insert the Homer Simpson drool noise here.

It was brunch time and we were hungry, but the large crowd outside did not scare us away. We went on inside and wrote our name down on the chalk board (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/brendas-french-soul-food-san-francisco?select=F7hDnfv5nXZieKACXkRMag#F7hDnfv5nXZieKACXkRMag). There wasn't that much space to wait inside, but we were lucky that two chairs opened up just as we stepped in. We waited patiently for about 15 minutes or so, before the host let us know that two bar seats opened up and asked whether we were interested. Apparently the bar seating was first come, first serve, and with the wait being over an hour estimate, we did not hesitate to say yes. We squeezed in at the bar and did not take any time to look at the menu, as we knew exactly what we wanted. We went with their infamous crawfish beignets, catfish benedict, andouille sausage and cheddar omelette and a glass of their sweet watermelon house tea. The sweet watermelon house tea was refreshing and not overly sweet. The crawfish beignets (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/brendas-french-soul-food-san-francisco#i8r1D2f0UqH54AfvuADkNw) were heavily spiced with cayenne and stuffed with a creamy mixture of crawfish, cheddar, and scallions. The beignet was fried like a doughnut, but had a similar texture to bread--slight chewiness, but surprisingly light. The cajun spices were abundant and the creamy mixture was rich and sweet. I really liked the contrasting texture of the scallions in the mixture and the dish was great, but I would have liked to see more crawfish. I felt like they were a tad bit skimpy on the crawfish. The catfish benedict (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/brendas-french-soul-food-san-francisco?select=RWWV_uNZROQbnEQLtnTT0w#i8r1D2f0UqH54AfvuADkNw) was my favorite. The catfish was fried to perfection with a perfect corn meal crust. The buttery biscuits were crispy outside, but nice and fluffy inside. The rich and creamy hollandaise sauce tied the catfish and biscuit altogether. The benedict was also served with a side of tasty potato hash. The andouille sausage omelette (http://www.yelp.com/biz_photos/brendas-french-soul-food-san-francisco?select=iM5eGmB-2ORJ64ukq1JI1A#iM5eGmB-2ORJ64ukq1JI1A) was simple, but good. It included mushrooms, scallions, and a large amount of sausage. Our waitress was very nice and even though they were super busy, she was patient and attentive. I haven't been to the great NOLA yet, but I hope Brenda's is remotely close to what it has to offer!

Had the special of the day which was the fried green tomato benedict. Also ordered the flight of beignets! I usually don't go for any type of eggs Benedict because my first experience with it honestly wasn't too great but since this place was known for it I just decided to try it! The service was awesome. Super nice and helpful with any questions you had. The green tomato Benedict was excellent. The tomato was still crisp and not mushy. There was also bacon on it and it was crunchy, nice contrast to the buttery biscuit underneath. The hollandaise was to DIE for. So rich and creamy and the poached egg was perfect. I also got the hash with it and it was nicely spiced. I'm not a big potato fan though so I wish I got the grits but still very good. Flight of beignets was amazing. I was too full though to try all four of them and just tried the chocolate and crawfish one. Both were amazing and honestly so, so, good. Worth it all the way. I was so pleased with their beignets considering that my only experience with beignets were the ones at Disneyland. Overall, I recommend this place. Only downside is location, it's in a sketch part of the city and parking is hard.

Oh my god, if you're into soul/southern food, come here immediately. If I were only in SF for a day, I would make it a point to visit this place. We actually came here twice -- we didn't know that the fried chicken benedict is only served on the weekends, so we went with the beef/grits and pork belly + cheesy grits. SO good. Came back that weekend to try the fried chicken benedict w/ hash. It's so amazing - creole hollandaise over fried chicken and cream biscuit, served w/ hash. Will DEFINITELY be back.

Everything was perfect! Service was great and all three of our meals were spectacular. I am not in S.F. often but I will try and get back here again

    Sitting at the front of Brenda's amid the casual whimsy of its New Orleans-inspired
    overtone with whispers of sophistication, I had an epiphany that the 5 pounds i had
    hoped to lose by summer would make no great difference in the grand scheme of

    plate to summon any forgotten syrup, I regretted nothing.

    strawberries with loving hands each morning or a carefully selected store-bought jar, i know not and care not for it tasted hopelessly delectable and was the most luscious pairing I could ever hope to again grace my plate for breakfasts to come.

    MUST GO.

    As I crossed the street toward Brenda's I saw a line that went around the corner and then some, and thought, "AW SHEEEEEEET" (and not the good kind). This would be my 3rd attempt at eating here without a 2 hour long wait. So, backup plan (always have a backup, even if it is saltine crackers that have been crushed by sitting on them) in my pocket: order to go.

    Crawfish beignets, cheese grits, cream biscuits, hash, the Hangtown Fry (crispy oyster, bacon, scallion scramble), Egg & Bacon Tartine...this was my TO GO order on our way to Napa.

    I think this was quite possibly the most delicious drive I've ever had. To coast on a drive with Brenda's cheese grits melting in your mouth...that's somethin' else.

    With 3 chalkboards worth of names willing to wait 2+ hours for a table, I think Brenda's has definitely earned its culinary street cred. Even my order took about 30-45 minutes, but it was well worth it. This is your true blue southern brunch at its best. It's the right amount of crunchy, buttery, savory...

    I still don't know that I could wait 2 hours to get a table here, but eating at Brenda's is like a giant Southern cream biscuit hugging your stomach and stroking / soothing you with an oversized strip of crispy bacon. Insert the Homer Simpson drool noise here.

    1 check-in

    It was brunch time and we were hungry, but the large crowd outside did not scare us away. We went on inside and wrote our name down on the chalk board (yelp.com/biz_photos/bren…). There wasn't that much space to wait inside, but we were lucky that two chairs opened up just as we stepped in. We waited patiently for about 15 minutes or so, before the host let us know that two bar seats opened up and asked whether we were interested. Apparently the bar seating was first come, first serve, and with the wait being over an hour estimate, we did not hesitate to say yes.

    We squeezed in at the bar and did not take any time to look at the menu, as we knew exactly what we wanted. We went with their infamous crawfish beignets, catfish benedict, andouille sausage and cheddar omelette and a glass of their sweet watermelon house tea. The sweet watermelon house tea was refreshing and not overly sweet.

    The crawfish beignets (yelp.com/biz_photos/bren…) were heavily spiced with cayenne and stuffed with a creamy mixture of crawfish, cheddar, and scallions. The beignet was fried like a doughnut, but had a similar texture to bread--slight chewiness, but surprisingly light. The cajun spices were abundant and the creamy mixture was rich and sweet. I really liked the contrasting texture of the scallions in the mixture and the dish was great, but I would have liked to see more crawfish. I felt like they were a tad bit skimpy on the crawfish.

    The catfish benedict (yelp.com/biz_photos/bren…) was my favorite. The catfish was fried to perfection with a perfect corn meal crust. The buttery biscuits were crispy outside, but nice and fluffy inside. The rich and creamy hollandaise sauce tied the catfish and biscuit altogether. The benedict was also served with a side of tasty potato hash.

    The andouille sausage omelette (yelp.com/biz_photos/bren…) was simple, but good. It included mushrooms, scallions, and a large amount of sausage.

    Our waitress was very nice and even though they were super busy, she was patient and attentive. I haven't been to the great NOLA yet, but I hope Brenda's is remotely close to what it has to offer!

    Had the special of the day which was the fried green tomato benedict. Also ordered the flight of beignets! I usually don't go for any type of eggs Benedict because my first experience with it honestly wasn't too great but since this place was known for it I just decided to try it!

    The service was awesome. Super nice and helpful with any questions you had. The green tomato Benedict was excellent. The tomato was still crisp and not mushy.     Overall, I recommend this place. Only downside is location, it's in a sketch part of the city and parking is hard.
